Both Lowe and Beer agree in considering these two MSS to be different parts of one whole. We have therefore here, in a single codex, the four works rediscovered by Poggio‚ as stated in the subscriptio of the Florentine MS of Asconius cited above. Lowe farther states that the Asconius and Valerius Flaccus, which are not in the same handwriting as the Manilius and Statius, may have been written by Poggio, to whom he seems also to ascribe the corrections on the first page of the Statius.

It is observable that all these witnesses speak of Manilius as re-dz'scoz’ered by Poggio. It is clear that they did not know of the existence of any other MSS, the Gemblacensis‚ Lipsiensis, or Cusanus. It may be inferred therefore with more than pro- bability that no copy of the Astronomica was then known to be extant in Italy. We may perhaps conclude that Poggio’s transcript of the S. Gallen MS was the parent of all the xvth century Italian codices.
